es 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Clyfton was born in 1165, in Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with William Chamberlain. She died in 1210, in her hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1165–1210":"1165–1210","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1195–1253":"1195–1253","1200–1260":"1200–1260","Abt 1195":"1195","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wickham, Hampshire, England":"Wickham, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1165–1210":"1165–1210","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1195–1253":"1195–1253","1200–1260":"1200–1260","Abt 1195":"1195","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1165":"1165","1253":"1253","1220":"1220","1195":"1195","1260":"1260","1160":"1160","Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wickham, Hampshire, England":"Wickham, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1165–12